  "summary": "An unnamed man visits Virginia Rue, presenting a private letter addressed to Captain O'Neil at 15 Paris Fish Circle. Although the letter is signed \"Virginia Ruff,\" Virginia informs the man that while it is her name, it is not her handwriting. The man reveals he found her via a newspaper clipping and claims to possess other letters—love letters written by a woman expressing fear of her husband being discovered. He demands a thousand pounds in exchange for the letters, which he characterizes as a business transaction rather than extortion. Virginia refuses the full amount but gives him forty pounds, instructing him to return the following day at six o'clock.\n\nAfter the man leaves, Virginia explains the situation to George Romax, who has arrived at the house. George is horrified that Virginia is allowing herself to be blackmailed, but Virginia remains composed and amused. She explains that she is not the woman who wrote the letters and views the encounter as a \"game and counter-game,\" believing she has effectively protected the true author by misleading the extortionist. \n\nFollowing this discussion, George asks Virginia for a favor. He explains that a Canadian man named McGregor is arriving in England the next day. George requests that Virginia meet McGregor to demonstrate the \"true charm and elegance of a British lady,\" as the man has not previously interacted with the British upper class.",
